Prepare Data¶

In [8]:
def prepare_datasets(df):
    data = df[['combined', 'sentiment']].copy() 
    # rename columns
    data.rename(columns={'combined':'text', 'sentiment':'label'}, inplace=True)
    # replace integers with text labels
    data['label'] = data['label'].map({0: 'neg', 1: 'pos', 2: 'mixed'})
    return data

train = prepare_datasets(X_train)
val = prepare_datasets(X_val)
test = prepare_datasets(X_test)
eyeball_val = prepare_datasets(X_eyeval)

Fine-Tune Bert¶

The fast-bert library was used to fine-tune a pytorch transfomer bert language model. Fast-bert is a Fast-AI inspired high level wrapper for the transformer architectures that works particularly well for fine-tuning these models to downstream classification tasks.

Create DataBunch Object¶

In [7]:
# The databunch object takes training, validation and test csv files and 
# converts the data into internal representation for BERT. 
# The object also instantiates the correct data-loaders based on device profile 
# and batch_size and max_sequence_length.

databunch = BertDataBunch(DATA_PATH, 
                          LABEL_PATH, 
                          tokenizer=args.model_name, 
                          train_file='train.csv', 
                          val_file='val.csv',
                          test_data='test.csv',
                          text_col="text", 
                          label_file='labels.csv',
                          label_col='label',
                          multi_label=False,
                          batch_size_per_gpu=args['train_batch_size'], 
                          max_seq_length=args['max_seq_length'], 
                          multi_gpu=True)

def bert_predictions(data, estimator, view_cm=True, 
                     normalize=True, logits=False):
    """ 
    Classify review sentiment using bert model.   
    
    Params:
    -----------
    data : pandas dataframe with text and label columns (same format as training).
    estimator : The fitted fast-bert model (learner object).
    view_cm : bool, default: True
              Plot confusion matrix.
    normalize : bool, default: True
                Return normalized confusion matrix.
    logits : bool, default: False
             If True returns logits from prediction, otherwise the softmax 
             probabilities are returned.  
    
    Return probabilities database and predictions array (class with highest
    estimate).
    """
    text = data.text.tolist()
    if logits:
        preds = estimator.predict_logits(text)
    else:
        preds = estimator.predict_batch(text)
        
    sorted_preds = [sorted(values) for values in preds]
    
    temp_labels = [y[0] for y in sorted_preds[0]]
    preds_df = pd.DataFrame([[y[1] for y in x] for x in sorted_preds], 
                             columns=temp_labels)

    probs_ordered = preds_df[['neg', 'pos', 'mixed']].copy()
    y_preds = np.argmax(probs_ordered.to_numpy(), axis=1)
    
    if view_cm:
        # transform text labels to integer inputs for confusion matrix
        if type(data['label']) is np.float64:
            y_test_numeric = data.label.values     
        else:
            y_test_numeric = data['label'].map({'neg': 0, 'pos': 1, 'mixed': 2}).values
    
        cm = confusion_matrix(y_test_numeric, y_preds)
        plot_confusion_matrix(cm, ['negative', 'positive', 'mixed'], 
                              normalize=normalize)

    return probs_ordered, y_preds

def get_scores(labels, preds, output_dict=True):
    """Return classification report for sentiment."""
    scores = classification_report(labels, preds, 
                                   target_names=['negative', 'positive', 'mixed'],
                                   output_dict=output_dict)
    return scores

How Confident were Mistakes?¶

Looking at whether the classifier made confident mistakes or not helps to determine how much control we have over filtering out incorrect predictions. For instance, if all mistakes are below .8 we could make the decision to send predictions below .8 to a human for a response. Confident mistakes are impossible to filter out this way.

  • Mixed (none above .41); positive (two above .9); negative (two above .9). Therefore, 4/17 (23.5%) were confident errors.
  • The rest were less confident border-cases.

Total Error = 17/500 = 3.4%
Confident Error = 4/500 = 0.8%


CONFIDENT ERRORS:
Two of the confident errors were ambiguous by human standards (i.e., the human judge probably used additional information (the rating) to determine the meaning of these reviews):

- "Usually awesome staff. Kids friendly. However if you a coffee lover. Watch out!"
- "Service!!!!"

For the unambiguous cases, one was mislabeled:

- "Half a smoothie was given to me and no straw."

While one was correctly labeled:

- "The service is on fire on another level."

Therefore, 2/4 (50%) of the confident errors were unambiguous (unavoidable) and can be classed as true and costly (undetectable) error. This is estimated at .4% of the entire dataset.

Avoidable Bias (underfitting):¶

Human error on this dataset is approximately 0.5-1%. The classifier is therefore underfitting by 2.5% (although only .4% confidentally). Considering that there are ~6% noisy labels, this underfitting may be unavoidable unless the labels are corrected. It is likely that training for more epochs will not fix the current error and may even result in the classifier overfitting to the noisy labels.

def correct_labels(df, threshold=0.5):
    """
    Replace incorrect labels. Use probability cutoffs for a 
    predicted class that conflict with current labels 
    to identify labels that are likely incorrect.
    
    Params:
    -------
    df: pandas dataframe with sentiment class probabilities and label
        columns.
    threshold: int, probability threshold for class prediction.
    
    Return dataframe with corrected labels and list of indexes 
    for corrected samples. 
    """
    df = df.copy()
    num_incorrect = 0
    for col in ['neg','pos','mixed']:
        idx = df.index[(df[col] > threshold) & (df.label != col)]
        for i in idx:
            df['label'][i] = col
        num_incorrect = len(idx)
    print('Number of Corrected Labels: {}'.format(num_incorrect))
    print('Total Percentage Changed: {}'.format(num_incorrect/len(df)*100))
    return df, idx

# threshold was gradually decreased for confidences from .95 to .5
# After corrections were made for each threshold, changes to the validation 
# labels were manually inspected. Results are presented below. 

train_corrected, _ = correct_labels(train_concat, threshold=0.8)
val_corrected, idx_corrected = correct_labels(val_concat, threshold=0.8)
test_corrected, _ = correct_labels(test_concat, threshold=0.8)

    (corrections.corrected + corrections.incorrect_amb)) / corrections.non_cum_totals)*100
corrections['cum_%_unamb'] = 100*(corrections.incorrect_unamb.cumsum() / corrections.non_cum_totals.cumsum())

Calibration¶

Return to Index

Probabilistic classifiers output a probability distribution over target classes, rather than just a prediction. The value of this distribution is that it represents the amount of uncertainty in those predictions. However, the probabilities outputted do not always accurately represent the amount of uncertainty - sometimes probabilities are over- or under-confident.

"Calibration - the idea that a model's predicted probabilities of outcomes reflect true probabilities of those outcomes - formalizes this notion"

NOTE: Custom methods were created for this multiclass calibration. See: calibration_methods.py and calibration_functions.py. Methods from the Netcal and Calibration libraries were used directly or adapted. Certain methods from this repo were also adapted NN Calibration.

Evaluation Metrics¶

Strictly proper scoring rules, as well as multiple calibration error metrics were used to evaluate calibration (in addition to the reliability diagrams and histograms).

CALIBRATION ERROR:
Expected Calibration Error: Discretize the probability interval into a fixed number of bins and assign predicted probabilities to each bin. The calibration error is the difference between the number of correct probabilities (accuracy) and the mean of all probabilities (confidence) for each bin.

Classwise ECE: The ECE calculated for each class.

Adaptive ECE: The Adaptive ECE focuses on those bins where predictions are made rather than weighing all bins equally. This metric spaces the bin intervals in such a way that each contains an equal number of predictions.

PROPER LOSSES:
Brier Score: "The Brier score measures the mean squared difference between (1) the predicted probability assigned to the possible outcomes for item i, and (2) the actual outcome. Therefore, the lower the Brier score is for a set of predictions, the better the predictions are calibrated." sklearn metrics

Negative Log-Likelihood: The NLL also average the error on every single instance to calculate the calibration error.

PROPORTION CORRECT/ INCORRECT:
F1-Macro weighted: The weighted average of the precision and recall. Calculate metrics for each label, and find their unweighted mean.

RELIABILITY DIAGRAMS:
When average confidence closely matches accuracy, the classifier is well calibrated. This can be seen in the reliability diagrams below. In the histrogram it is the distance between the grey and black lines, and for the binned confidence any deviation from the perfect diagonal represents miscalibration (visually represents ECE).

A combination of proper scoring and calibration error metrics give a well rounded view on miscalibration and improvements made.

Temperature Scaling¶

An extension of Platt scaling, this method essentially maximizes the entropy of the ouput probability subject to certain constraints (it "softens" the softmax function applied to the logits, but does not change the maximum of the function. Class prediction therefore stays the same and the accuracy is unchanged). In other words, the probabilities are scaled by reducing overconfidence (increasing entropy) without changing predictions. This ensures that the probability estimates better approximate true probabilities and prevent overfitting via minimization of error, in this case NLL (negative log likelihood).

This is a post-processing method that does not change the learnt parameters/ weights of the model, but rather optimizes temperature (T) with respect to NLL on the validation logits.

Dirichlet Scaling¶

Temperature scaling only has a single tunable parameter and therefore cannot learn to act differently on different classes. Dirichlet scaling is applies better to multiclass models, able to calibrate each class more effectively.

To apply Dirichlet scaling the log probabilities are provided as inputs to a Multinomial Logistic Regression model. The model is fitted on the validation probabilties and the test probabilities are used for evaluation.

Conclusion¶

The fast-bert model performed better than the XGBoost model, and required less preprocessing. The fast-bert framework was added to the AWS ecosystem and the classifier was made available as an endpoint. After an evaluation period, it will be decided whether the probabilities should be calibrated, and if so, the prefered method will be added as a post-processing function.
